Incident.Summary: Responded to the Dash In Willard's for a robbery at gun point.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Incident Type: Robbery 
Suspect: Unknown 
Victim: Jesse Thomas Braden 05-14-1996 #443-669-8113
Other contact people:
    - Manager - Jennifer Ann Gravenor 09-25-1984 # 443-397-1903
    - Business owner - Greg Grevey #410-835-8836
Scene processing: I responded to the scene and collect all the information required and locked down the scene until the crime scene arrived at the scene to investigate. 
 
Narrative: 
On 02-28-2023 at 1112 hours I, TFC. Norfolk 7120 responded to the Dash In Willard's located at 7201 Main St, Willard's MD 21874 for a robbery at gunpoint. 

I arrived at the scene and met with the victim identified as Jesse Thomas Braden. Braden advised that an unknown black male that was approximately 6ft 4in tall approximately 180lbs came into the store at 1107 hours before going straight to the back of the store towards the bathroom. Braden did not pay the subject any attention due to the normal foot traffic in the store at this time of night. Braden said that he walked back up to the register when the subject came from behind the shelving displaying a black semi-automatic handgun. Braden said the subject pointed the handgun at his face demanding the money in the register. Braden gave the subject all the money in the drawer which came to $213.96 dollars. Braden said the subject then left the store getting back into a small silver sedan he believed was a Toyota. 
    I met with the manager of the store who was not working at the time of the robbery. She was identified as Jennifer Ann Gravenor. Gravenor advised that the owner she identified as Greg Grevey was not answering his cell phone. Gravenor was asked if she was able to look at the security cameras for the store. She advised that she could but that she does not know how to send the footage only Grevey knows how to do that. 
     In the video footage, you can see a small silver sedan drive around the parking lot 3-4 times parking in different areas around the building until it was empty of customers. The vehicle then pulls up facing the building at pump number seven before the front seat passenger exits the vehicle and approaches the store with no mask covering his face. The subject then enters the building and makes an immediate right going toward the coolers on the back wall. While doing this the subject pulls his mask over his face and ducks down behind the shelving to hide. The subject then goes back towards the bathroom out of sight of Braden. In the video, you can see Braden approach the register after eating some food. This is when the subject came from across the store pointing the black handgun at Braden demanding the money. Once the subject gets the money and is leaving the store he uses his right hand to open the glass door by pushing on it with his hand. The subject then gets back into the vehicle and heads down Main St in the direction of Old Ocean City Rd. You can see the vehicle make a left turn at the intersection heading west in the direction of Salisbury Maryland. 

Crime scene and CED were contacted to respond to the scene.  Cpl. Hager with the Criminal Enforcement Division responded to the scene as the primary investigator. Crime scene arrived at the scene and completed their investigation. Crime Scene was provided a case number along with Cpl. Hager's information. Cpl. Hager was able to recover the video footage from the security system for Gravenor.

All events occurred in Wicomico County MD. 

I request this case be left open pending transfer to CED for further investigation. 
Case open

Narrative: 
On February 28, 2023, at approximately 2325 hours [11:25 p.m.] I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region was contacted by the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack in reference to an armed robbery which occurred at the Dash In located at 7201 Main Street, Willards, Wicomico County, Maryland 21874. After being contacted by the Salisbury Barrack, I learned that at approximately 2312 hours troopers from the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack were dispatched to the Dash In for an armed robbery. Troopers arrived and contacted the store clerk Jesse Thomas Braden [hereinafter referred to as Braden], who advised a black male entered the store, went to the rear of the store, came to the register and displayed a black handgun as he demanded money.  Braden described the suspect tall and thin dressed in all black clothing and wore a mask covering his face when he approached Braden. The suspect exited the store and fled the scene in a small silver passenger car believed to be a Hyundai. 

I responded to the scene and conducted an interview of Braden, who provided a similar statement as listed above and said approximately 213 dollars in US Currency was obtained by the suspect.  I reviewed video surveillance and were able to view the suspect enter the store without a mask over his face.  I observed the silver vehicle travel throughout the parking lot before parking near the gas pumps. The male suspect can be seen exiting the front passenger side of the vehicle and walking across the parking lot towards the front of the store. In the video, it does not appear that the suspect wore gloves. As the suspect exited the store he placed his hand on the glass front door.  After the robbery, the suspect vehicle leaves the parking lot and travels north on Main Street prior to making a left turn onto westbound Old Ocean City Road.  I observed the front door to have only had two to three fingerprints that were visible and Braden said that the glass door had been cleaned during the morning hours of February 28, 2023. 

Crime scene Technicians from the Maryland State Police Forensic Sciences Division were contacted and responded to the scene for scene processing.

Case open, investigation continuing.

Narrative: 
On March 1, 2023, at approximately 0052 hours [12:52 a.m.], I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region conducted an interview of Jesse Thomas Braden [hereinafter referred to as Braden]. The interview was recorded and was conducted in my Maryland State Police assigned Chevrolet Malibu [CE-150]. Below is a synopsis of the interview and not a transcript therefore some paraphrasing may be used:
  • Braden started his shift at 2200 hours [10:00 p.m.] however he was approximately fifteen minutes late to work
  • Braden was the only employee working at the Dash In on February 28, 2023
  • Braden observed the suspect walk into the Dash In and go to the right
  • Braden could not see the suspect’s face but it did not look like he had a mask on at the time
  • Braden thought the suspect went to the bathroom
  • Braden walked away from the register and then came back to the register at which time the suspect approached him
  • Braden said the suspect “put a gun on me” and Braden gave the suspect everything in the register
  • Braden described the suspect to be a black male and the same build as Braden
  • Braden said the suspect was approximately 6ft 4inches and approximately 170 lbs
  • Braden described the suspect to be wearing a black sweat suit with white stripes on the pants
  • Braden described the suspect’s shoes to be black shoes that looked like “air forces” but Braden was not paying attention to the suspects shoes
  • Braden described the suspect’s gun as a semiautomatic black handgun with approximately 7 inch barrel
  • Braden said the gun appeared to be a real gun and described it as all metal and the end was wide
  • Braden said the gun did not look like a BB gun and the barrel appeared to be real from what he knows
  • Braden said the suspect began waving the gun and then pointed the gun at him and towards the drawer
  • Braden said he was scared
  • Braden said the suspect then began to give him demands
  • Braden said he handed the suspect the money
  • Braden said the suspect had the gun in one hand and Braden put the money in the suspects other hand
  • Braden did not observe any tattoos on the suspects hands due to everything happening so fast
  • Braden thought the suspect had gloves on and described the suspects hands to be just as dark as the gun
  • Braden said the suspect exited the store and Braden then locked the front door and called 911
  • Braden said he has not seen the suspect before
  • Braden said the suspect had a ski mask on, but he did not recognize the suspects build or voice
  • Braden described the suspect vehicle to be a silver vehicle that he believed to be a Toyota sedan with a newer body style
  • Braden also observed the suspect vehicle to be parked at the gas pump
  • Braden could not tell if the suspect was by himself or not however he observed the suspect get into the passenger seat of the vehicle
  • Braden does not recall seeing the driver of the vehicle at all
  • Braden said that he was talking to a customer prior to the robbery and the customer said that his biggest anxiety was getting robbed while closing the store
  • Braden described the customer to drive an older silver Ford Taurus in his early 40s with “salt and pepper” hair and beard
  • Braden cannot recall anyone that he has recently had an argument with
  • Braden believed the suspect was provided with approximately 200 dollars
  • Braden said he provided the suspect with 20-dollar bills, 10-dollar bills, 5-dollar bills, and 1-dollar bills
  • Braden provided me with a receipt/ shift report from the cash register from when he cashed out which showed a total of $213.96. Braden said the $213 is the cash that was given to the suspect.
Case open, investigation continuing.

Narrative: 
On March 1, 2023, I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region checked the Dash In for any physical evidence related to the armed robbery. As I entered the Dash In, I observed fingerprints/ hand prints located on the glass of the right front door which appeared to be recent. I observed that the glass appeared to be recently cleaned. I was able to briefly review the Dash In surveillance footage and observed as the suspect exited the store he placed his uncovered right hand directly on the interior glass of the door behind a white sign that was on the exterior of the door. I checked the portion of the glass which I observed the suspect touch on the surveillance footage and observed fingerprints/ partial hand print. The Maryland State Police Crime Scene Unit was contacted and Crime Scene Technician Linda Idso [hereinafter referred to as CST Idso] responded. CST Idso processed the crime scene and recovered the following: 
  • Two (2) Latent Lift Cards
  • One (1) swab possible DNA from interior glass door front left side
CST Idso took possession of the above listed items and transported them to the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack where they were stored.

Dash In manager Jennifer Gravenor allowed me to access, review, and copy the Dash In video surveillance footage. The video surveillance footage was stored on a Datastick pro USB flash drive which I took possession of. I later responded to the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack where I stored the USB flash drive in temporary storage. 

Case open, investigation continuing.

Narrative: 
On February 28, 2023, and March 1, 2023, I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region was able to review the Surveillance camera footage from the Dash In. I observed the Dash Ins camera system to be displaying the correct date and time. Below is a timeline of events which I was able to observe from the video:
 
  • 22:39:05 – Suspect vehicle enters the parking lot of the Dash In from the northwest entrance. I observed the vehicle to be a silver Hyundai Accent or Elantra with no front registration plate and dark tinted windows. The suspect vehicle proceeds to the front of the Dash In.
  • 22:39:17- Suspect vehicle drives past the front door to a green Kia Rio [later identified as belonging to Jesse Thomas Braden] which is parked in the 6th parking space from the west side of the Dash In and comes to a stop. At this time, I observed the suspect vehicle to have no rear registration plate and an inoperative left tag lamp. The suspect vehicle then backs up directly in front of gas pump #6.
  • 22:39:40 – The suspect vehicle pulls into the 5th parking space from the west side of the Dash In and parks. The suspect vehicle remains parked in this parking space running with the lights on until 22:58:42.
  • 22:58:42 – The suspect vehicle backs out of the parking space #5 and proceeds to the west side of the Dash In. 
  • 22:59:09 - The suspect vehicle continues to the west side of the Dash In. 
  • 22:59:18 - The suspect vehicle pulls into the north-most parking space on the west side of the Dash In. The suspect vehicle pulls into the parking space and then backs up slightly. The suspect vehicle can be observed with what appears to be duct tape on the passenger mirror and the front bumper appears to be separated from the passenger front fender. The suspect vehicle also has a red "tree" air freshener hanging from the interior rear view mirror. The video footage shows two occupants of the vehicle which appear to be a black female driver with something white on her head and a black male passenger.  While parked in this parking space the suspect vehicle can be observed parked next to a silver Chrysler minivan bearing Maryland Registration 5DT4220.  
  • 22:59:31 - The passenger in the suspect vehicle opens the door and exits the vehicle. The passenger stands outside the vehicle with the passenger door open. The passenger is a black male wearing a black hooded sweatshirt and black pants with dual white stripes on the thigh area. The passenger stands outside the vehicle and looks around the parking lot and the Dash In. 
  • 22:59:53 - The passenger gets back inside the vehicle and shuts the door. The suspect vehicle's passenger front window can be observed partially down and the passenger can be observed moving around in the passenger seat of the vehicle. The suspect vehicle remains parked in this parking space until 23:03:20.
  • 23:00:12 - The driver of the silver Chrysler minivan exits the Dash In and enters the silver Chrysler.
  • 23:03:20 - The suspect vehicle backs out of the parking space and begins traveling towards the front of the Dash In.
  • 23:03:40 - The suspect vehicle can be observed traveling east in the parking lot past the entrance to the Dash In. The suspect vehicle continues through the parking lot and travels to the south side of the gas pumps located in the parking lot. The suspect vehicle then continues west in the parking lot.
  • 23:04:13 - The suspect vehicle can again be observed traveling east in the parking lot past the entrance to the Dash In and traveling to the south side of the gas pumps.
  • 23:04:36 - The suspect vehicle can be observed pulling up to gas pump #9 with the front of the vehicle facing the Dash In where it remains until 23:05:02.
  • 23:05:02 - The suspect vehicle can be observed pulling away from gas pump #9 and turning left. The suspect vehicle then travels west past the entrance of the Dash In.
  • 23:05:28 - The suspect vehicle then travels east on the south side of the gas pumps.  
  • 23:05:39 - The suspect vehicle can again be observed pulling up to gas pump #9 with the front of the vehicle facing the Dash In.
  • 23:05:44 - The suspect vehicle begins to back away from gas pump #9 and travels west 
  • 23:06:00 - The suspect vehicle pulls up to gas pump #7 with the front of the vehicle facing the Dash In
  • 23:06:04 - The passenger of the suspect vehicle exits the vehicle and begins walking to the entrance of the Dash In. The passenger of the suspect vehicle can be identified as the suspect and can be described as a tall black male wearing a black hooded sweatshirt, black pants with dual white stripes on the thigh area and black shoes. When approaching and entering the store the suspect is not observed wearing a mask.
  • 23:06:23 - The suspect approaches the front door of the Dash In, opens the door with his right hand, and enters the Dash In.
  • 23:06:27 - The suspect can be observed walking inside the Dash In and making a right turn towards the rear of the store without a mask.
  • 23:06:30 - The suspect can be observed pulling an all black ski mask over his face with no gloves on
  • 23:06:44 - The suspect can be observed walking in a ducking position and entering the rear restroom area of the store.
  • 23:08:18 - The suspect can be observed exiting the rear restroom area with a mask on and walking down the coffee aisle towards the cash register.
  • 23:08:26 - The suspect can be observed approaching the cashier identified as Jesse Thomas Braden [hereinafter referred to as Braden] with a handgun. The suspect can be observed pointing a handgun at Braden.
  • 23:08:28 - The suspect can be observed at the cash register with a black handgun in his left hand. The suspect is waiving the handgun and pointing it at Braden
  • 23:08:32 - Braden can be observed opening the cash register and handing the US Currency from the register to the suspect. Braden can be observed placing the US Currency in the suspect's right hand. The suspect's hands can be observed, and no gloves are present on them.
  • 23:08:48 - The suspect runs towards the front door of the Dash In and exits by placing his right hand on the glass of the left exit door. The suspect can be observed with his right hand touching the glass directly behind a white sign that is on the exterior of the glass.
  • 23:08:49 - The suspect can be observed exiting the Dash In and running to the passenger side of the suspect vehicle.
  • 23:08:55 - The suspect enters the front passenger seat of the suspect vehicle as the vehicle is pulling away from gas pump #7
  • 23:09:01 - The suspect vehicle pulls away from gas pump #7 and travels west in front of the Dash In with no headlights on.
  • 23:09:05 - The suspect vehicle can be observed exiting the Dash In parking lot at a high rate of speed utilizing the north-west exit of the parking lot.
  • 23:09:25 - The suspect vehicle can be observed traveling west on Old Ocean City Road.    
Case open, investigation continuing.

I conducted an Maryland Motor Vehicle Administration check of the vehicle's registration which revealed that it was registered to Daniel Neal St Clair [hereinafter referred to as St Clair].

On March 2, 2023, I contacted St Clair by telephone and was able to conduct a phone interview with him. Below is a synopsis of the interview conducted with St Clair.

  • St Clair described the employee as a male who was excentric and talked about his boyfriend to St Clair in the past

Narrative: 
Photo Line Up:
On March 20, 2023, at approximately 0917 hours [9:17 a.m.] Ross Cameron Holbrook [hereinafter referred to as Holbrook] responded to the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack to view a photo line up. Senior Trooper Garrett Dick #6158 [hereinafter referred to as S/T Dick] of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region presented Holbrook with the photo line up while I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 observed. S/T Dick read Holbrook the photo array instructions utilizing a Maryland State Police Form 193 which Holbrook signed. S/T Dick provided Holbrook with each of the six (6) photographs individually. Upon viewing photograph number four (4) Holbrook identified the photograph as Joshua David Johnson [hereinafter referred to as Johnson]. Holbrook was asked without using a numerical scale, how certain he was to which Holbrook responded Positive 200%.

Interview:   
After reviewing the photo line up, I conducted an interview with Holbrook. The interview was conducted in the interview room at the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack and was recorded. Below is a synopsis of the interview and not a transcript therefore some paraphrasing may be used: 
  • Holbrook attends the House of Prayer Church in Selbyville, Delaware where Johnson also attends
  • Holbrook said Johnson's brother [Holbrook could not remember Johnson's brothers name] also attends the same church and told Holbrook his brother [Johnson] has gone crazy
  • Holbrook's wife told him to look at Facebook
  • Holbrook looked at Facebook and observed the photographs to be of Johnson prior to contacting the Salisbury Barrack 
  • Holbrook was asked by the church to talk to Johnson
  • Holbrook urged Johnson to turn himself in
  • According to Holbrook, Johnson said "I'm not going to jail"
  • Holbrook said Johnson carries a black gun which Holbrook described to look like a 9mm on his right hip
  • Holbrook said Johnson also carries a knife
  • Holbrook knows Johnson to spend time with an unknown female 
  • Holbrook said the female drives a vehicle which he described to be the gray car which he observed in the photographs 
  • Holbrook said that during his conversations with Johnson about the Dash In Johnson said that he needed money, so he robbed the store
  • According to Holbrook, Johnson said if he needs more money it will happen again
  • Holbrook said Johnson is very bold and does not hide
  • Holbrook said Johnson could be staying at the House of Prayer Church or Hickory Tree Daycare
  • Holbrook said that Johnson's mother Alisa Johnson is a pastor at the House of Prayer Church
Case open, investigation continuing.

Narrative: 
On May 23, 2023, at approximately 1037 hours, I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region was able to conduct an interview with Joshua David Johnson [hereinafter referred to as Johnson]. Johnson was being extradited from Delaware to Maryland when he made the utterance that he "did it" and that he wanted to confess. Johnson was read his Miranda Rights by Senior Trooper Garrett Dick, #6158 utilizing a Maryland State Police Form 180. Due to Johnson being handcuffed and transported in my Maryland State Police issued Chevrolet Malibu [CE-150] Johnson was unable to sign the Maryland State Police 180 however he verbally advised that he understood and agreed to waive his rights. The interview took place inside CE-150 and was recorded. Below is a synopsis of the interview and not a transcript therefore some paraphrasing may be used:
  • I told Johnson that I wanted to speak to him about the incident at the Dash In on February 28, 2023, to which Johnson stated "Yes that was me" 
  • Johnson said the gun he utilized was not a real gun only a BB gun which is now in the custody of the Selbyville Delaware Police Department 
  • Johnson said he painted the BB gun black because it had an orange tip
  • Johnson believes that the cashier Jesse Thomas Braden [hereinafter referred to as Braden] was the only one in the store
  • Johnson said Amaya Elaine Judy Counts [hereinafter referred to as Counts] didn't know that he was going to rob the store
  • Johnson told Counts they were going to the Dash In to get some wings
  • Johnson said he removed the registration plate from Counts' vehicle
  • Johnson said his house was at the Talbot Apartments
  • Johnson said he and Counts went to the Dash In and sat in the car and smoked 
  • Johnson said he was wearing his work clothes which include a ski mask, black hoodie, black sweatpants with a white stripe and shoes
  • Johnson said he asked Counts to go to Uncle Willies and get him a black ski mask approximately two days prior
  • Johnson said the ski mask was for work at the chicken plant
  • Johnson said Counts was scared and did not really understand what was going on
  • Johnson described his relationship with Counts to be a girlfriend/ friend, and they mess around
  • Johnson said Counts doesn't know how to say no 
  • Johnson said he was drunk and being jittery
  • Johnson said they sat in the car for approximately 30 minutes smoking until he got out of the car stretched his legs and got back into the car
  • Johnson told Counts that he could see in the window and there were no wings
  • Johnson told Counts to pull to the other side of the store and she did so 
  • Johnson told Counts to pull to the gas pumps he was about to go inside
  • Johnson entered the store and went into the bathroom 
  • Johnson looked in the mirror in the bathroom and said "are you really about to do this what the fuck is wrong with you"
  • Johnson said he had to do it, and he didn't have a choice
  • Johnson walked out of the bathroom and pointed the gun at Braden and said "the money from the cash register"
  • Johnson said that Braden was getting a drink just prior
  • Johnson said Braden jumped and told him to chill
  • Johnson said Braden opened the cash register and told Johnson there grab it 
  • Johnson told Braden to grab the money
  • Johnson said he received $232
  • Johnson said he was not wearing gloves
  • Johnson said he had to do it because he had been in a car accident and was in a tight situation with money
  • Johnson said it was him just trying to get some money fast and was having financial issues
  • Johnson said he was drinking alot and doing drugs which was taking money from him
  • Johnson said Counts would help him get money
  • Johnson said he was kind of taking advantage of Counts
  • Johnson said there was no 9mm or a knife
  • Johnson said the BB gun did not have any BB's in it 
  • Johnson said he fights, but he doesn't get into "gun shit"
  • Johnson said his intention was never to hurt anyone and if he could apologize to Braden he would
  • Johnson did not have anything against Braden he just happened to be working that night
  • Johnson said Braden looked like and easy target
  • Johnson said that justice has to be justice, and he has to deal with the consequences of his actions
  • Johnson said his purple phone has a number, but he doesn't know the number and the black phone is turned off
  • Johnson said he also had a blue phone which he lost while he was on the run
  • Johnson said he does not think there is anything in reference to the incident at the Dash In on any of his phones 
  • Johnson said he does not have any guns at his house however his apartment has already been cleaned out since he's been in Jail
  • Johnson said there was nothing else he wanted to tell me about the incident at the Dash In other than he took the money, and he left
Case closed by arrest.
